123
00:10:13.187 --> 00:10:15.889
Guys. guys! That's <i>if</i>
that were to happen. Right?

124
00:10:15.956 --> 00:10:18.058
They're gonna figure this out.

125
00:10:18.125 --> 00:10:23.564
Right now. the best minds
in the entire world are on it.

126
00:10:38.169 --> 00:10:46.142
Well. I woke up Sunday morning with no
way to hold my head that didn't hurt...

127
00:10:48.757 --> 00:10:51.025
<i>Good morning. Dr. Grace.</i>

128
00:10:51.992 --> 00:10:53.827
I'm up!

129
00:11:02.451 --> 00:11:10.251
Then I headed back for home and somewhere
far away a lonely bell was ringing.

130
00:11:14.576 --> 00:11:22.576
And it echoed through the canyons like
the disappearing dreams of yesterday.

131
00:11:24.701 --> 00:11:32.701
On the Sunday Morning
sidewalk wishing Lord I was stoned.

132
00:11:36.728 --> 00:11:44.728
Cause there's something in a
Sunday makes a body feel alone.

133
00:11:48.622 --> 00:11:56.622
And there's nothing short of
dying half as lonesome as the sound.

134
00:12:00.358 --> 00:12:08.358
On the sleeping city sidewalk
Sunday morning coming down.

135
00:12:32.359 --> 00:12:34.027
Knock. knock.

136
00:12:35.929 --> 00:12:36.930
Who's there?

137
00:12:36.997 --> 00:12:38.298
Not good at jokes.

138
00:12:38.365 --> 00:12:40.134
Not good
at jokes who?

139
00:12:43.705 --> 00:12:45.372
Dr. Grace?

140
00:12:46.974 --> 00:12:48.475
Maybe.

141
00:12:48.542 --> 00:12:49.953
Eva Stratt. I'm with
the Petrova Task Force.

142
00:12:49.977 --> 00:12:51.278
I need your help.

143
00:12:51.864 --> 00:12:52.613
Me.

144
00:12:52.680 --> 00:12:54.281
Did you write this?

145
00:12:57.223 --> 00:12:58.252
Oh.

146
00:12:58.318 --> 00:12:59.854
I'm interested in this section here.

147
00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:01.455
Uh -Page 31.

148
00:13:01.522 --> 00:13:03.290
"The Goldilocks Zone Is For Idiots:

149
00:13:03.357 --> 00:13:05.827
Why Everyone Is Wrong About Life."

150
00:13:06.293 --> 00:13:07.662
That was a long time ago.

151
00:13:07.729 --> 00:13:08.949
Do you stand by what you wrote?

152
00:13:08.973 --> 00:13:11.699
I was fired for standing by what I wrote.

153
00:13:11.766 --> 00:13:13.233
You were fired

154
00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:15.235
for calling the leading
scholar in your field

155
00:13:15.302 --> 00:13:16.805
"a staggering waste of carbon"

156
00:13:16.871 --> 00:13:18.706
at the UNESCO conference in Denmark.

157
00:13:19.012 --> 00:13:21.208
You heard about that. huh?

158
00:13:21.275 --> 00:13:23.678
Look. I don't know what this is.

159
00:13:23.745 --> 00:13:26.714
but. uh. I think I'm not s...

160
00:13:26.781 --> 00:13:27.948
That's lava.

161
00:13:28.015 --> 00:13:29.616
- It's not.
- Okay.

162
00:13:29.684 --> 00:13:32.052
No one in your field
wants anything to do with you

163
00:13:32.119 --> 00:13:33.396
because you refused to back down

164
00:13:33.420 --> 00:13:35.255
from a very unpopular view.

165
00:13:35.322 --> 00:13:36.834
and I can give you a chance
to prove them all wrong.

166
00:13:36.858 --> 00:13:38.793
Uh Kevin. no running.

167
00:13:38.860 --> 00:13:40.461
I'm not.

168
00:13:40.527 --> 00:13:43.731
Well. joke's on them because
I don't even care. So.

169
00:13:44.866 --> 00:13:46.333
I think you do care.

170
00:13:46.400 --> 00:13:48.040
You're running away
because you're scared.

171
00:13:48.068 --> 00:13:49.603
No. I'm not.

172
00:13:51.104 --> 00:13:52.504
Do you still believe water

173
00:13:52.539 --> 00:13:54.441
is unnecessary for life to evolve?

174
00:13:54.508 --> 00:13:55.677
Uh.

175
00:13:56.076 --> 00:13:59.613
Look. there is nothing magical
about hydrogen and oxygen.

176
00:13:59.681 --> 00:14:02.149
Water is required for life on Earth. sure.

177
00:14:02.216 --> 00:14:03.718
But a completely different planet

178
00:14:03.785 --> 00:14:05.428
might have completely
different conditions.

179
00:14:05.452 --> 00:14:07.092
I don't know why
that makes me such a nut.

180
00:14:07.120 --> 00:14:09.089
I need you to come with us.

181
00:14:10.257 --> 00:14:11.501
Sorry. I didn't catch your name.

182
00:14:11.525 --> 00:14:12.593
Carl.

183
00:14:12.660 --> 00:14:14.328
- Carl. Hi.
- Dr. Grace.

184
00:14:14.394 --> 00:14:15.749
Petrova line samples
splashed down last night.

185
00:14:15.773 --> 00:14:19.166
I want you to tell me
what they are. how they work.

186
00:14:19.233 --> 00:14:22.069
I am a teacher
at Grover Cleveland Middle.

187
00:14:22.135 --> 00:14:23.814
And you have a doctorate
in molecular biology.

188
00:14:23.838 --> 00:14:27.842
And I ride a bike to work.
and it's not for exercise.

189
00:14:27.909 --> 00:14:29.149
So I'm sure there are thousands

190
00:14:29.209 --> 00:14:30.116
of other people who are better...

191
00:14:30.141 --> 00:14:31.942
It survives on the surface of the sun.

192
00:14:31.967 --> 00:14:34.007
Does that sound like
a water-based life form to you?

193
00:14:41.255 --> 00:14:42.790
The sun's really dying. isn't it?

194
00:14:42.857 --> 00:14:44.491
Yeah.

195
00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:51.576
Is all of this necessary?

196
00:14:52.876 --> 00:14:54.278
Yes.

197
00:14:54.366 --> 00:14:56.999
<i>Please analyze the Petrova sample.</i>

198
00:14:57.024 --> 00:14:58.338
Um.

199
00:14:58.405 --> 00:14:59.974
<i>Just one thing.</i>

200
00:15:00.040 --> 00:15:01.251
The entire room is filled with argon.

201
00:15:01.275 --> 00:15:03.110
Just try not to rip your suit.

202
00:15:03.873 --> 00:15:05.275
Uh.

203
00:15:07.303 --> 00:15:09.918
Am I expendable?
Is that why you want me?

204
00:15:09.984 --> 00:15:11.686
That's not the only reason.

205
00:15:11.711 --> 00:15:14.054
It's almost like you don't care if I die.

206
00:15:18.525 --> 00:15:21.061
Hold on. You have to talk about it?

207
00:15:21.393 --> 00:15:22.994
The consensus here

208
00:15:23.019 --> 00:15:25.888
is that it would be preferable
if you did not die.

209
00:15:27.234 --> 00:15:28.378
Thanks. guys.

210
00:15:35.609 --> 00:15:37.344
Oh.

211
00:15:42.282 --> 00:15:44.652
Welcome to Earth.

212
00:15:58.911 --> 00:16:01.046
Are they alive?

213
00:16:01.268 --> 00:16:02.502
They're moving.

214
00:16:02.569 --> 00:16:04.104
So they're alive.

215
00:16:04.171 --> 00:16:05.673
Yes. they're moving.

216
00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:07.909
but that could be for many reasons.

217
00:16:07.976 --> 00:16:09.509
What are they made of?

218
00:16:09.576 --> 00:16:11.578
It's gonna take a long ti...
It took like 200 years

219
00:16:11.645 --> 00:16:13.748
to figure out how bacteria works. so.

220
00:16:13.815 --> 00:16:15.649
Please do it faster.

221
00:16:17.719 --> 00:16:20.722
I'm just going through
the whole light spectrum here.

222
00:16:21.257 --> 00:16:22.458
Wow!

223
00:16:24.092 --> 00:16:26.126
You're not gonna believe this.

224
00:16:28.613 --> 00:16:29.913
Nothing happened.

225
00:16:34.725 --> 00:16:37.295
I can't see into these buggers.

226
00:16:39.473 --> 00:16:40.808
Amazing.

227
00:16:40.875 --> 00:16:44.712
X-rays. microwaves.
gamma rays. visible light.

228
00:16:44.779 --> 00:16:46.413
Nothing!

229
00:16:47.715 --> 00:16:50.918
Ooh. ooh. ooh. I've been
dying to do this all day!

230
00:17:07.735 --> 00:17:09.070
It's a cell!

231
00:17:09.137 --> 00:17:11.571
It's a cell. Wake up! It's a cell!

232
00:17:11.630 --> 00:17:14.901
It's a tiny alien cell.
You guys!

233
00:17:14.976 --> 00:17:16.343
Applause.

234
00:17:16.410 --> 00:17:19.546
Guys! This is first contact!

235
00:17:20.048 --> 00:17:22.850
With life outside of the...!

236
00:17:23.350 --> 00:17:24.752
Uh-oh.

237
00:17:25.185 --> 00:17:26.520
Oh. it died.

238
00:17:26.586 --> 00:17:28.355
What?

239
00:17:29.356 --> 00:17:30.825
This is great news.

240
00:17:30.892 --> 00:17:33.193
Now we can find out
what they're made of.

241
00:17:35.495 --> 00:17:37.431
You guys fired up?

242
00:17:40.295 --> 00:17:41.729
Yes!

243
00:17:42.016 --> 00:17:43.219
Right?

244
00:17:44.172 --> 00:17:45.773
Carbon.

245
00:17:46.165 --> 00:17:47.866
Oxygen.

246
00:17:50.048 --> 00:17:51.817
Hydrogen.

247
00:17:52.212 --> 00:17:53.715
Oh.

248
00:18:07.787 --> 00:18:09.622
It's made

249
00:18:11.833 --> 00:18:13.835
almost entirely

250
00:18:15.568 --> 00:18:17.236
of water.

251
00:18:26.550 --> 00:18:28.652
All right.

252
00:18:30.785 --> 00:18:33.154
Sorry if I overreacted in there.

253
00:18:33.654 --> 00:18:36.289
Just. uh. realizing I was wrong

254
00:18:36.356 --> 00:18:38.226
about the only original idea I ever had.

255
00:18:38.291 --> 00:18:39.927
Yeah. What else did you learn?

256
00:18:39.994 --> 00:18:42.262
They give off infrared light
when they move.

257
00:18:42.329 --> 00:18:43.330
Mm-hm.

258
00:18:43.396 --> 00:18:44.126
Like. so much.

259
00:18:44.150 --> 00:18:45.939
I don't know how
they store all that energy.

260
00:18:45.964 --> 00:18:50.634
But. uh. their wavelength is
exactly the Petrova frequency.

261
00:18:51.612 --> 00:18:52.931
The light is how they move.

262
00:18:52.956 --> 00:18:55.176
Yeah. they consume the sun's energy.

263
00:18:55.243 --> 00:18:57.344
and then they expel it for propulsion.

264
00:18:57.410 --> 00:18:59.446
They toot to scoot basically.

265
00:19:00.939 --> 00:19:03.383
Why did it go to Venus?

266
00:19:04.564 --> 00:19:06.131
I don't know.

267
00:19:07.887 --> 00:19:09.257
Okay. We'll tell you.

268
00:19:09.322 --> 00:19:10.758
What?

269
00:19:10.825 --> 00:19:13.326
I have 347 other biologists
in 21 countries

270
00:19:13.393 --> 00:19:15.029
mobilizing as we speak.

271
00:19:15.096 --> 00:19:17.564
So thank you for your help.
I'm glad you didn't die.

272
00:19:17.631 --> 00:19:18.900
Let's pack this up.

273
00:19:18.966 --> 00:19:20.701
Pack up!

274
00:19:23.436 --> 00:19:25.173
That's it?

275
00:19:25.239 --> 00:19:27.041
- That's it. Carl?
- Talk to her.

276
00:19:27.108 --> 00:19:28.408
You're taking all the stuff?

277
00:19:28.475 --> 00:19:30.211
At the school you said

278
00:19:30.278 --> 00:19:32.122
there were thousands of people
more qualified than you. so

279
00:19:32.146 --> 00:19:34.414
- I was being modest.
- I don't need modest.

280
00:19:34.481 --> 00:19:35.961
I need people who think they're right

281
00:19:36.017 --> 00:19:37.652
when everyone else
thinks they're wrong.

282
00:19:37.718 --> 00:19:39.196
I need people who piss other people off.

283
00:19:39.220 --> 00:19:40.320
That's me!

284
00:19:40.387 --> 00:19:42.156
Do you want to be on a project?

285
00:19:42.223 --> 00:19:44.324
If you.

286
00:19:44.391 --> 00:19:47.360
If you think I can help. then.

287
00:19:47.427 --> 00:19:49.396
Just answer the question.

288
00:19:49.462 --> 00:19:51.364
I wanna help the world.

289
00:19:51.431 --> 00:19:53.000
I left you three dots.

290
00:19:53.067 --> 00:19:54.401
Just three. huh?

291
00:19:54.467 --> 00:19:56.037
Plus the one you killed.

292
00:19:56.314 --> 00:19:58.016
I would take the three.

293
00:20:00.270 --> 00:20:01.872
- Yes?
- I'll take the dots.

294
00:20:01.976 --> 00:20:03.679
Get to work. Dr. Grace.

295
00:20:05.193 --> 00:20:07.663
The world is counting on you.

296
00:21:15.195 --> 00:21:16.730
<i>Hey. Carl?</i>

297
00:21:17.936 --> 00:21:19.136
This is Carl.

298
00:21:19.202 --> 00:21:20.772
Imagine for a second

299
00:21:20.838 --> 00:21:23.308
that you're an interstellar microorganism.

300
00:21:23.374 --> 00:21:25.443
I'm not doing that.

301
00:21:26.811 --> 00:21:29.681
Why would you
leave the sun and go to Venus?

302
00:21:29.747 --> 00:21:32.750
Why not stop at Mercury? It's closer.

303
00:21:34.084 --> 00:21:35.820
Maybe fresh air?

304
00:21:35.887 --> 00:21:37.956
Venus's atmosphere
is mostly CO2.

305
00:21:38.022 --> 00:21:39.624
Maybe that's fresh air to them.

306
00:21:39.691 --> 00:21:41.759
You don't know what
these little space dots like.

307
00:21:46.898 --> 00:21:48.032
<i>Hey. Carl?</i>

308
00:21:48.309 --> 00:21:49.934
Do we have an expense account?

309
00:21:50.001 --> 00:21:51.836
We don't.

310
00:21:56.007 --> 00:21:57.342
But I do.

311
00:22:28.506 --> 00:22:30.441
All right. I got something for you.

312
00:22:40.985 --> 00:22:42.453
Thank you.

313
00:22:42.520 --> 00:22:44.197
- Do you have a coupon?
- We don't need a coupon.

314
00:22:44.221 --> 00:22:46.004
- We're the government.
- Which government?

315
00:22:46.030 --> 00:22:47.565
All of 'em.

316
00:22:49.535 --> 00:22:50.928
So this box is Venus.

317
00:22:50.995 --> 00:22:52.597
The box is Venus.

318
00:22:52.664 --> 00:22:54.832
It's set to emit the same
infrared light frequency

319
00:22:54.899 --> 00:22:56.567
as Venus's CO2 atmosphere.

320
00:22:56.634 --> 00:22:58.770
So if the dots move
when you turn the lights on.

321
00:22:58.836 --> 00:23:01.506
that means they're looking for CO2.

322
00:23:01.572 --> 00:23:04.108
Thus proving the Carl Hypothesis.

323
00:23:04.174 --> 00:23:05.175
Sick.

324
00:23:07.264 --> 00:23:08.664
Sorry.

325
00:23:08.808 --> 00:23:10.029
- All right.
- All right.

326
00:23:10.053 --> 00:23:11.822
You ready?

327
00:23:15.319 --> 00:23:17.187
Uh-oh.

328
00:23:17.254 --> 00:23:18.723
Why you saying "Uh-oh"?

329
00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:20.858
The Astrophage
moved off the slide.

330
00:23:20.925 --> 00:23:22.093
Huh?

331
00:23:22.160 --> 00:23:23.695
We lost them.

332
00:23:23.761 --> 00:23:25.897
What do you mean.
we lost them? Go get them.

333
00:23:26.263 --> 00:23:27.865
If I open the door in the light.

334
00:23:27.932 --> 00:23:30.101
they're gonna escape. and then
we'll lose them forever.

335
00:23:30.168 --> 00:23:31.502
At least now they're in the box.

336
00:23:31.569 --> 00:23:33.504
So we'll just turn the lights off.

337
00:23:33.571 --> 00:23:34.757
But there'll still be light.
It's gotta be total darkness.

338
00:23:34.781 --> 00:23:37.540
Okay. so just put this box in another box.

339
00:23:45.983 --> 00:23:47.385
Nice.

340
00:23:58.801 --> 00:24:01.238
Go ahead and close it. Over.

341
00:24:01.629 --> 00:24:03.297
I can hear you.

342
00:24:08.739 --> 00:24:11.009
Entering phase two.

343
00:24:16.414 --> 00:24:17.949
I'm in.

344
00:24:23.182 --> 00:24:25.318
<i>Please report. Over.</i>

345
00:24:27.791 --> 00:24:29.461
<i>There's one.</i>

346
00:24:30.862 --> 00:24:31.963
<i>There's two!</i>

347
00:24:32.030 --> 00:24:34.266
Come on! Get the third one.

348
00:24:36.134 --> 00:24:37.902
<i>Got sample three.</i>

349
00:24:37.969 --> 00:24:40.205
<i>The Three Musketeers.
The Three Stooges.</i>

350
00:24:43.774 --> 00:24:44.943
<i>Uh-oh.</i>

351
00:24:45.010 --> 00:24:47.012
What? What?

352
00:24:47.912 --> 00:24:49.681
<i>Are you sitting down?</i>

353
00:24:49.748 --> 00:24:51.349
No. I'm standing like a grown man.

354
00:24:51.826 --> 00:24:53.918
<i>'Cause there's a fourth.</i>

355
00:24:54.552 --> 00:24:55.854
What?

356
00:24:57.689 --> 00:25:00.158
<i>We're fathers. Carl.</i>

357
00:25:02.193 --> 00:25:04.496
Now I'm sitting down.

358
00:25:07.397 --> 00:25:08.397
<i>Stratt.</i>

359
00:25:08.662 --> 00:25:11.336
Carl and I made a baby.

360
00:25:11.606 --> 00:25:12.804
<i>What?</i>

361
00:25:12.871 --> 00:25:14.673
We figured out how Astrophage breeds.

362
00:25:15.874 --> 00:25:17.409
<i>Don't move.</i>

363
00:25:19.311 --> 00:25:20.812
Wheels up.

364
00:25:21.846 --> 00:25:23.257
You know. Carl.

365
00:25:23.281 --> 00:25:25.517
when Stratt said she was sending a jet.

366
00:25:25.583 --> 00:25:27.261
I thought you meant
like a PJ or something.

367
00:25:27.285 --> 00:25:30.322
- I know.
- Take this.

368
00:25:31.456 --> 00:25:33.091
Been a long time since I've taken a pill

369
00:25:33.158 --> 00:25:34.735
from a stranger
without knowing what it was.

370
00:25:36.928 --> 00:25:38.963
Oh my God! Stop!

371
00:25:49.341 --> 00:25:51.409
Dr. Grace. how was your flight?

372
00:25:56.715 --> 00:25:58.483
- Where are we?
- The ocean.

373
00:25:58.550 --> 00:26:01.453
The Astrophage reproduction.
Can you do it at scale?

374
00:26:01.519 --> 00:26:05.590
Oh. in theory. you just get
a bunch of elbow-shaped pipe.

375
00:26:05.657 --> 00:26:06.958
put sunlight in one end...

376
00:26:07.025 --> 00:26:08.360
Excuse me for a second.

377
00:26:09.794 --> 00:26:11.138
- Write it down.
- Yes. ma'am.

378
00:26:12.697 --> 00:26:15.667
and IR light and CO2
in the other. Repeat.

379
00:26:15.734 --> 00:26:16.877
Anything else you need for...

380
00:26:16.901 --> 00:26:18.436
Just some water.

381
00:26:18.503 --> 00:26:19.847
He gave me a pill
and it's still in my throat.

382
00:26:19.871 --> 00:26:21.172
Two venti coffees.

383
00:26:21.239 --> 00:26:22.741
Thank you so much. Water for him.

384
00:26:22.808 --> 00:26:23.908
Or coffee. That's

385
00:26:23.975 --> 00:26:25.477
I need both.

386
00:26:25.543 --> 00:26:26.945
Or not.

387
00:26:27.011 --> 00:26:28.189
Okay. so this is kind of a tough room.

388
00:26:28.213 --> 00:26:29.849
so don't take it personally.

389
00:26:29.914 --> 00:26:31.383
I don't need anything fancy.

390
00:26:31.449 --> 00:26:34.018
As long as there's a bed
and a shower I'm good.

391
00:26:38.523 --> 00:26:40.468
- I can't do this.
- Come on. Yes.

392
00:26:40.492 --> 00:26:42.370
- I can't. I can't.
- You're doing great.

393
00:26:42.394 --> 00:26:44.763
Everyone. this is Dr. Ryland Grace

394
00:26:44.830 --> 00:26:46.064
from the United States.

395
00:26:46.131 --> 00:26:48.299
Please go here. Thank you.

396
00:26:48.366 --> 00:26:51.536
And he figured out
how to breed Astrophage.

397
00:26:56.876 --> 00:26:58.376
How did you do it?

398
00:26:58.443 --> 00:27:00.121
How long
does the process take?

399
00:27:00.145 --> 00:27:02.280
Does it reproduce by mitosis or meiosis?

400
00:27:02.347 --> 00:27:04.749
<i>What is the incubation period?</i>

401
00:27:05.984 --> 00:27:07.752
Um

402
00:27:08.854 --> 00:27:11.723
Carl and I made a mini Venus
out of a plywood box.

403
00:27:12.123 --> 00:27:14.426
and as soon as the samples recognized

404
00:27:14.492 --> 00:27:17.996
the. uh. spectral signature
of CO2. they were.

405
00:27:19.964 --> 00:27:21.801
They were like. "Whoomp! There it is!"

406
00:27:21.867 --> 00:27:22.934
Okay.

407
00:27:23.001 --> 00:27:24.602
You can sit down.

408
00:27:25.092 --> 00:27:26.171
Who's Carl?

409
00:27:26.237 --> 00:27:27.748
While your experiment
was crude and clumsy.

410
00:27:27.772 --> 00:27:30.108
our scientists have replicated his results.

411
00:27:32.655 --> 00:27:34.679
I'm sorry. how did you see...?

412
00:27:34.746 --> 00:27:36.781
We estimate an eight-day doubling time

413
00:27:36.849 --> 00:27:38.049
under optimal conditions.

414
00:27:38.116 --> 00:27:40.485
- Dr. Grace is right.
- Oh.

415
00:27:40.552 --> 00:27:41.986
It is the CO2.

416
00:27:42.053 --> 00:27:43.431
That's why
they're going to Venus.

417
00:27:43.455 --> 00:27:44.956
Please say it for everyone.

418
00:27:45.023 --> 00:27:46.383
That's why they're going to Venus.

419
00:27:46.424 --> 00:27:49.360
So that's why they're going to Venus.

420
00:27:49.427 --> 00:27:51.262
is what Dr. Grace wants to say.

421
00:27:51.329 --> 00:27:52.940
They're going to breed.

422
00:27:52.964 --> 00:27:54.834
Whoomp! There it is.

423
00:27:56.534 --> 00:27:58.169
I really like him.

424
00:27:58.236 --> 00:28:00.806
How long to make two million kilogram?

425
00:28:00.873 --> 00:28:02.540
Two million?

426
00:28:04.175 --> 00:28:05.510
Two million is...

427
00:28:05.577 --> 00:28:06.711
Why

428
00:28:08.279 --> 00:28:10.748
on earth would you need
that much Astrophage?

429
00:28:10.816 --> 00:28:13.151
Nobody told him?

430
00:28:13.618 --> 00:28:14.752
He has no clearance.

431
00:28:14.820 --> 00:28:16.754
Please stand up. Dr. Grace.

432
00:28:17.489 --> 00:28:18.656
Stand up.

433
00:28:19.424 --> 00:28:21.259
I hereby grant you top-secret clearance

434
00:28:21.326 --> 00:28:24.162
to all information pertaining
to Project Hail Mary.

435
00:28:25.129 --> 00:28:27.065
What's Project Hail Mary?

436
00:28:28.700 --> 00:28:30.001
All right.

437
00:28:33.037 --> 00:28:35.406
The sun is not the only star dying.

438
00:28:35.473 --> 00:28:37.709
There is a clear pattern of infection.

439
00:28:37.775 --> 00:28:41.881
Every star was infected
by its neighbor except one.

440
00:28:41.947 --> 00:28:43.314
Tau Ceti?

441
00:28:43.381 --> 00:28:45.016
That's right. 11.9 light years away.

442
00:28:45.083 --> 00:28:46.784
It is uninfected

443
00:28:46.852 --> 00:28:48.930
despite being well within
the cluster of infected stars.

444
00:28:48.954 --> 00:28:49.955
Why?

445
00:28:50.054 --> 00:28:51.155
Why? Tell him.

446
00:28:51.222 --> 00:28:52.624
We don't know!

447
00:28:52.690 --> 00:28:55.059
Which is why we decided to build a ship

448
00:28:55.126 --> 00:28:56.862
to go there and find out.

449
00:28:56.929 --> 00:28:58.329
It's 11.9 light years away.

450
00:28:58.396 --> 00:29:00.833
You can't just build an interstellar ship.

451
00:29:00.900 --> 00:29:02.166
Oh yeah. we can.

452
00:29:02.233 --> 00:29:03.802
The ship is not really the problem.

453
00:29:03.869 --> 00:29:07.205
The energy required to power
the ship is the problem.

454
00:29:07.272 --> 00:29:08.640
It was the problem.

455
00:29:10.553 --> 00:29:12.303
The Astrophage is the fuel.

456
00:29:12.328 --> 00:29:14.345
Provided we can make enough of it.

457
00:29:14.412 --> 00:29:17.382
And for that. we need you. my friend.

458
00:29:19.584 --> 00:29:20.886
Me?

459
00:29:20.953 --> 00:29:23.856
Ooh. Those little guys
store a lot of energy.

460
00:29:24.255 --> 00:29:25.891
One mistake and that much Astrophage

461
00:29:25.958 --> 00:29:28.059
could vaporize California.

462
00:29:28.126 --> 00:29:30.261
That's true. which is why
you now live on a boat

463
00:29:30.328 --> 00:29:32.096
in the middle of the ocean in case

464
00:29:33.565 --> 00:29:35.633
- I live on a boat?
- You do.

465
00:29:35.700 --> 00:29:38.303
So you wanna build
a near-light speed spaceship.

466
00:29:38.369 --> 00:29:40.772
have it travel further
than any human-made object

467
00:29:40.839 --> 00:29:42.140
has ever traveled.

468
00:29:42.206 --> 00:29:45.844
and visit a star just to "see what's up"?

469
00:29:46.092 --> 00:29:47.012
Yeah.

470
00:29:47.078 --> 00:29:48.646
And then what?

471
00:29:48.713 --> 00:29:50.591
There won't be
enough fuel for a round-trip

472
00:29:50.615 --> 00:29:54.085
so they send their findings
back to Earth on probes.

473
00:29:56.120 --> 00:29:59.157
And the astronauts

474
00:30:01.912 --> 00:30:03.467
die in space?

475
00:30:03.492 --> 00:30:04.926
Yes.

476
00:30:07.032 --> 00:30:08.801
Space.

477
00:30:12.071 --> 00:30:14.606
Any other plans you've thought of?

478
00:30:14.672 --> 00:30:17.508
Anything else you're kicking around?

479
00:30:17.575 --> 00:30:19.945
There are infinite possibilities

480
00:30:20.012 --> 00:30:21.512
for this to go wrong.

481
00:30:21.579 --> 00:30:23.214
It almost certainly won't work.

482
00:30:23.281 --> 00:30:25.750
It's what you Americans
would call a long shot.

483
00:30:26.250 --> 00:30:27.820
Hail Mary.

484
00:30:28.119 --> 00:30:29.454
I get it now.

485
00:30:29.520 --> 00:30:33.191
The alternative is to just do nothing

486
00:30:33.758 --> 00:30:35.861
and to starve and to kill each other

487
00:30:35.928 --> 00:30:38.217
and watch everything
on this planet go extinct.

488
00:30:38.242 --> 00:30:39.743
including us.

489
00:30:40.191 --> 00:30:41.326
So.

490
00:31:01.820 --> 00:31:04.295
That's a long time to be in space.

491
00:31:04.320 --> 00:31:06.491
They'll be in comas for most of it.

492
00:31:06.609 --> 00:31:08.176
But is that even safe?

493
00:31:08.243 --> 00:31:10.512
Nothing about this is safe.

494
00:31:25.060 --> 00:31:26.595
<i>We only need three.</i>

495
00:31:27.496 --> 00:31:28.597
<i>A pilot.</i>

496
00:31:28.664 --> 00:31:30.666
<i>An engineer.</i>

497
00:31:30.733 --> 00:31:33.168
<i>And a scientist.</i>

498
00:31:37.740 --> 00:31:39.475
Commander Yáo.

499
00:31:41.477 --> 00:31:44.379
I must have known you.
but I just don't remember.

500
00:31:45.080 --> 00:31:47.683
You make a funny face

501
00:31:47.750 --> 00:31:52.220
in literally every picture.

502
00:31:52.287 --> 00:31:55.390
<i>You must have been very smart</i>

503
00:31:55.458 --> 00:31:56.559
<i>and strong</i>

504
00:31:58.360 --> 00:31:59.928
and brave.

505
00:32:03.733 --> 00:32:05.033
Ilyukhina.

506
00:32:06.167 --> 00:32:08.771
First. I owe you three bags of vodka.

507
00:32:10.123 --> 00:32:12.240
<i>You seemed to have had a lot of friends.</i>

508
00:32:12.775 --> 00:32:14.175
<i>This picture of you.</i>

509
00:32:14.242 --> 00:32:17.646
what looks like sneaking into the Kremlin

510
00:32:19.381 --> 00:32:20.483
is legendary.

511
00:32:23.118 --> 00:32:25.253
<i>I wish you were still here.</i>

512
00:32:26.522 --> 00:32:28.657
<i>I wish I wasn't alone.</i>

513
00:32:28.724 --> 00:32:30.626
I wish I was

514
00:32:31.477 --> 00:32:33.945
doing a better job. I just. uh.

515
00:32:38.584 --> 00:32:40.752
You were both very loved.

516
00:32:42.355 --> 00:32:43.822
You deserve much more than this.

517
00:32:46.224 --> 00:32:47.826
I'll do my best

518
00:32:47.892 --> 00:32:49.794
to make sure that you don't

519
00:32:51.755 --> 00:32:54.025
you know. that you didn't...

520
00:33:06.278 --> 00:33:08.046
I'll do my best.

521
00:34:13.211 --> 00:34:15.548
<i>Approaching Tau Ceti orbit.</i>

522
00:34:15.614 --> 00:34:16.848
<i>Prepare for engine cutoff.</i>

523
00:34:18.384 --> 00:34:19.984
<i>Fourteen. thirteen</i>
What?

524
00:34:20.051 --> 00:34:21.520
Why engine cutoff?

525
00:34:21.587 --> 00:34:24.155
Seems like something
we should talk about.

526
00:34:24.222 --> 00:34:25.957
<i>Pilot detected.</i>

527
00:34:26.024 --> 00:34:28.093
What? No. I'm not a pilot!

528
00:34:28.159 --> 00:34:29.729
<i>Four. three.</i>

529
00:34:29.795 --> 00:34:32.030
What happens at zero? I mean...

530
00:34:39.672 --> 00:34:41.940
<i>You are now orbiting Tau Ceti.</i>

531
00:34:44.943 --> 00:34:48.714
What the fudging fudger?

532
00:34:51.350 --> 00:34:53.753
<i>Petrov a scope operational.</i>

533
00:34:53.819 --> 00:34:56.121
<i>Petrov a scope operational.</i>

534
00:35:17.008 --> 00:35:18.377
It's Tau Ceti.

535
00:35:29.087 --> 00:35:31.624
You have a Petrova line.

536
00:35:31.954 --> 00:35:33.559
But you're not dimming.

537
00:35:33.626 --> 00:35:35.628
Why?

